        <body>

            <pb n="4"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">2</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F35</name>
                    <desc>(BIRD OF PARADISE)	ornamental birds: bird of paradise</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE TOUCAN.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">This bird is a native of South<lb/>America,
                very conspicuous for the<lb/>bigness and shape of its bill. The<lb/>monkies are his
                bitter enemies ;<lb/>they often attack his nest, but Pro&ndash;<lb type="inWord"
                />vidence has allotted him a head and<lb/>beak of such a size, as to fill up
                the<lb/>whole entrance of his nest ; and<lb/>when the plunderer approaches,<lb/>the
                bird gives him such a rough<lb/>welcome, that the monkey is glad<lb/>to run
                away.</p>

            <pb n="5"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">3</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure>
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F36</name>
                    <desc>water-birds</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE PENGUIN.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">This bird is never seen far from<lb/>shore, and
                it is therefore, a sure in&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>dication to the seamen, who
                observe<lb/>it, that land is near. Its legs are<lb/>placed very far back, which
                makes<lb/>the bird a bad walker ; but it swims<lb/>and dives well. It walks
                erect,<lb/>when on the land, and makes a<lb/>very curious sight.</p>

            <pb n="6"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">4</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure>
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F38</name>
                    <desc>(OSTRICH)	walker and runner birds: ostrich</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE OSTRICH.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">This is the largest of birds, it<lb/>being ten
                feet in height, when it<lb/>raises its head. It is a glutton in<lb/>eating, for it
                will devour leather,<lb/>glass, iron, bread and hair, as well<lb/>as other food. The
                eggs of an Os&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>trich are about the size of an
                infant's<lb/>head. The Ostrich is hunted for<lb/>its feathers, the surpassing
                beauty<lb/>of which is well known. These<lb/>fine feathers are from the tail
                of<lb/>the bird.</p>

            <pb n="7"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">5</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F37</name>
                    <desc>(CRANE)	shore-birds and wading-birds: crane</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE CRANE.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">These birds fly from the south in<lb/>the
                Spring, and spend their Sum&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>mer in northern regions.
                Their<lb/>flight is generally so high, that they<lb/>are rarely observed. They may
                be<lb/>seen afar off, with their long necks<lb/>stretched out, and slim legs
                    hang&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ing behind, with slow steady flap,<lb/>the sight
                of which has often de&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>lighted us. They sometimes
                utter<lb/>a shrill cry, which can be heard two<lb/>miles.</p>

            <pb n="8"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">6</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F32</name>
                    <desc>(WREN)	song-birds: wren</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE WREN.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">This little gossip usually makes<lb/>her nest
                near the garden, in some<lb/>box or crevice of a tree ; or she will<lb/>put up with
                an old hat, nailed<lb/>against the weather&ndash;boards, with a<lb/>small bole for
                an entrance. They<lb/>hate a cat ; they have been seen<lb/>to fly at puss, who sat
                in the gar&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>den, and snap their little beak
                very<lb/>spitefully close to her ears, while<lb/>puss would strike back with
                her<lb/>swift paw, trying to catch the bird.</p>

            <pb n="9"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">7</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F39</name>
                    <desc>(CUCKOO)	other birds: cuckoo</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE CUCKOO.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The song of this bird is closely<lb/>connected
                with our ideas of reviv&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ing spring. When singing,
                this<lb/>bird is very seldom seen, as his<lb/>shyness induces him to hide
                himself<lb/>in thickets.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The European Cuckoo is sup&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>posed to build no nest, and, what is<lb/>extraordinary, the
                female Cuckoo<lb/>deposits her solitary egg in the nest<lb/>of another bird, by
                which it is<lb/>hatched.</p>

            <pb n="10"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">8</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F39</name>
                    <desc>(WOODPECKER)	other birds: woodpecker</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE WOODPECKER.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The Woodpecker makes his nest<lb/>by digging
                with his beak into the<lb/>trunk or limb of some decayed tree,<lb/>forming a
                circular cavity, in which<lb/>the eggs are deposited, and the<lb/>young ones
                hatched.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">He climbs along the trunks of<lb/>trees, and
                discovers by the appear&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ance of the bark, where the
                insect<lb/>is lurking. The multitude of cat&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>erpillars,
                bugs, and worms which<lb/>one of these birds devours in a day<lb/>is surprising.</p>

            <pb n="11"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">9</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F38(PHEASANT)</name>
                    <desc>walker and runner birds: pheasant</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE PHEASANT.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The Pheasant of Europe, in shape<lb/>and
                plumage, is one of the most<lb/>elegant of birds. It was originally<lb/>brought from
                the banks of the river<lb/>Phasis, in Asia Minor, whence it<lb/>derives its name. It
                is beautifully<lb/>marked with various brilliant hues.<lb/>The cock Pheasant is
                considerably<lb/>larger, his tail longer, and his plu&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>mage
                more brilliant than that of the<lb/>hen Pheasant.</p>

            <pb n="12"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">10</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F35</name>
                    <desc>(PEACOCK)	ornamental birds: peacock</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE PEACOCK.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The plumage of this bird is more<lb/>gorgeous
                and beautiful than any<lb/>other of the feathered race. Its<lb/>form is also elegant
                ; and, as if con&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>scious of these personal
                advantages,<lb/>it often spreads its gaudy tail, and<lb/>marches about with a
                pompous<lb/>step, apparently vain of its beauty,<lb/>and anxious to display to the
                eye of<lb/>the beholder, its rich and changing<lb/>hues. Yet the Peacock is
                nearly<lb/>an useless bird, and its voice harsh.</p>

            <pb n="13"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">11</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F35</name>
                    <desc>(PARROT)	ornamental birds: parrot</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE PARROT.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">Some years since, a parrot in<lb/>Boston, that
                had been taught to<lb/>whistle in the manner of calling a<lb/>dog, was sitting in
                his cage at the<lb/>door of a shop. As he was whistling<lb/>one day, a large dog
                happened to<lb/>be passing. The animal imagining<lb/>that his master called him,
                turned<lb/>suddenly about and ran towards the<lb/>cage. Just then the bird
                exclaimed<lb/>&ldquo; Get out, you brute !&rdquo; The dog<lb/>scampered quickly
                away.</p>

            <pb n="14"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">12</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F39</name>
                    <desc>(HUMMING-BIRD)	other birds: humming-bird</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE HUMMING BIRD.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">There are seventy kinds of Hum&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>ming Birds, nearly all of them na&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>tives
                of America, yet only one kind<lb/>visits the United States. He fre&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>quents the gardens, and sips the ho&ndash;<lb type="inWord"
                />ney&ndash;suckle and other plants, like<lb/>the hive and humble bee.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The nest of this bird is very small,<lb/>and is
                beautifully lined with the<lb/>down of the mullen.</p>

            <pb n="15"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">13</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F32</name>
                    <desc>(JAY)	song-birds (BLUE JAY)</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE BLUE JAY.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">This elegant bird is distinguished<lb/>as a
                kind of beau among the feather&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ed tenants of our woods, by
                the<lb/>brilliancy of his dress, and, like<lb/>most other coxcombs, makes
                    him&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>self still more noted by his noise,<lb/>and the
                oddness of his tones and<lb/>gestures. In the charming season of<lb/>Spring, when
                every thicket pours<lb/>forth harmony, the part performed<lb/>by the Jay always
                catches the ear.</p>

            <pb n="16"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">14</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F3</name>
                    <desc>birds</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE STORMY PETREL.</p>
            <p rend="align(centre)"><hi rend="italics">Or Mother Carey's Chickens.</hi></p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">This bird is about the size of a<lb/>swallow.
                It is seen in all parts of<lb/>the ocean, busily engaged in search&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>ing for food. It braves the storm,<lb/>skimming along the waves,
                    some&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>times above the tops, then again by<lb/>sinking
                down into the billows be&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>tween them. It does not sit
                upon<lb/>the water, but often places its feet<lb/>it, while feeding.</p>

            <pb n="17"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">15</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F36</name>
                    <desc>(SWAN)	water-birds: swan</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE SWAN.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">The Swan is the largest of
                all<lb/>web&ndash;footed water&ndash;fowl, some of<lb/>them weighing above 20 lbs.
                The<lb/>whole body is covered with a beau&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>tiful
                lily&ndash;white plumage. The ele&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>gance of his form, which
                this bird<lb/>displays, when, with his arched<lb/>neck and half displayed wings,
                he<lb/>sails along the crystal surface of the<lb/>stream, which reflects, as he
                passes,<lb/>the snowy beauty of his dress, is<lb/>worthy of admiration.</p>

            <pb n="18"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">16</fw>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>25F37</name>
                    <desc>(WOODCOCK)	shore-birds and wading-birds: woodcock</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE WOODCOCK.</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(2) align(justify)">During the day, this bird sleeps<lb/>in the
                woods and thickets, and at<lb/>the approach of evening seeks the<lb/>springs, and
                open marshy places,<lb/>to feed in. It usually feeds in the<lb/>night. Its flesh is
                reckoned very<lb/>delicious, and no game is more<lb/>prized by sportsmen. It is
                about<lb/>as large as a Quail, and has a bill<lb/>three inches long.</p>
            <p rend="align(centre)">THE END.</p>
